Wrapper"><div class=3D"body__inner-container"><p>I am not what anyone would=
 call a math person, but I am a scrappy cook, which occasionally means I ha=
ve to bust out the calculator (...app on my phone). Scaling recipes up and =
down requires some finagling, but if you keep your eyes on the prize, you c=
an easily quadruple a <a href=3D"https://www.epicurious.com/recipes-menus/s=
atisfying-summer-salads-gallery">salad</a> for a party or translate a giant=
 <a href=3D"https://www.epicurious.com/recipes-menus/love-is-a-rich-lasagna=
-gallery">lasagna</a> into a romantic dinner for two. Cooking is nice that =
way: With a little common sense and basic multiplication skills (again, or =
an app), almost any recipe can be modified to fit almost any scenario.</p><=
p>Baking, on the other hand, is a different story. Because your <a href=3D"=
https://www.epicurious.com/recipes/food/views/cocoa-brownies-51134540">brow=
nies</a> and <a href=3D"https://www.epicurious.com/recipes-menus/our-favori=
te-birthday-cakes-gallery">birthday cakes</a> rely on chemical reactions an=
d exact leavening agent measurements to succeed, scaling up or down or chan=
ging the pan size necessitates a bit more precision.</p><div><div class=3D"=
